│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe pass separates constant    │
│ offsets from GEP indices by tracing into arithmetic and cast operations  │
│ and then rebuilding the expression. In the provided reproducer, the pass │
│ moves a trunc with nsw from after an add to before the add, effectively  │
│ transforming `trunc nsw (add i128 %i, 1)` into `add (trunc nsw i128 %i   │
│ to i64), 1`. This can introduce poison, because the semantics of nsw on  │
│ trunc mean the result is poison if the truncated value cannot be         │
│ represented in the destination type under the specified signed/unsigned  │
│ constraints. Moving a poison-generating trunc across arithmetic changes  │
│ when poison is triggered and can make the transformed IR more poisonous  │
│ than the source.\n\nAlive2 confirms this: the target becomes poison,     │
│ while the source remains a concrete pointer. This indicates an invalid   │
│ transformation related to the handling of trunc with nsw/nuw.\n\n2.      │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt output shows the first transformation      │
│ point in ConstantOffsetExtractor::distributeExtsAndCloneChain. The       │
│ transformed IR truncates %i directly to i64 (with nsw), then performs a  │
│ GEP using that, followed by a byte-level GEP of +4, corresponding to the │
│ element size. The log shows that the pass traced through a trunc and     │
│ copied/ext-distributed casts.\n\nThe code path involved:\n- find()       │
│ treats TruncInst by unconditionally tracing through it: it recursively   │
│ finds a constant offset in the operand and then truncates the APInt.\n-  │
│ distributeExtsAndCloneChain collects cast instructions (including trunc) │
│ in ExtInsts and later applies them to operands via applyExts,            │
│ effectively moving the trunc earlier in the expression chain.\n- There   │
│ is some consideration for NUW preservation in allowsPreservingNUW, but   │
│ it only checks trunc's NUW and does not address NSW. Moreover,           │
│ preservation of NUW here is about deciding if reassociation can preserve │
│ GEP's nuw, not general poison safety for casts.\n\n3. Root Cause         │
│ Analysis:\nThe root cause is that find() and distributeExtsAndCloneChain │
│ treat trunc uniformly, regardless of poison-generating flags (nsw/nuw).  │
│ Unconditionally tracing through a trunc and redistributing it across     │
│ binary operators changes the timing and conditions under which poison    │
│ may be produced. In particular, moving a trunc nsw across an add/sub     │
│ without corresponding wrap guarantees is unsound, and can make the       │
│ result more poisonous than the original expression, as demonstrated by   │
│ the counterexample.\n\nThe existing comment near allowsPreservingNUW     │
│ recognizes that trunc without nuw can be problematic when distributed    │
│ through add nuw, but the actual tracing in find() does not guard against │
│ trunc with any wrap flags. We need to avoid tracing through trunc if it  │
│ has nsw/nuw, unless we can prove safety—which we currently do not.\n\n4. │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit the handling of TruncInst in               │
│ ConstantOffsetExtractor::find() to avoid tracing through                 │
│ poison-generating truncs. Only trace through plain trunc (without        │
│ nsw/nuw). If a trunc has nsw or nuw, treat it as a barrier and do not    │
│ attempt to extract through it.\n\nEdit Point:\n- File:                   │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/SeparateConstOffsetFromGEP.cpp\n- Lines:      │
│ 606-614\n- Change:\n  Replace the unconditional tracing for TruncInst    │
│ with a guard:\n\n  } else if (isa<TruncInst>(V)) {\n    // Do not trace  │
│ through poison-generating truncs (nsw/nuw). Moving such\n    // casts    │
